-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - Sept 12
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Thu Sep 11, 2014 10:30PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, Sept 12 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- The Securities and Futures Commission filed a court order against state-backed conglomerate Citic <0267.HK> and five former directors, including chairman Larry Yung Chi-kin, seeking a total of HK$1.9 billion ($245 million) in compensation for 4,500 investors that the regulator says suffered losses due to the firm's failure to report massive forex trading losses in 2008. (http://bit.ly/1nPeo83) -- The Jockey Club has had another bonanza year as its net margin jumped to HK$9.78 billion ($1.26 billion), thanks largely to record horse racing turnover. Takings from soccer betting and the Mark Six lottery also rose. Racing turnover jumped 10.1 percent to a record HK$103.9 billion for the fiscal year that ended in June. (http://bit.ly/1xQBKUx) -- Beijing is under fresh pressure to implement another round of policy easing, including a rate cut, with mainland inflation falling to a four-month low and money supply growth the lowest in five months. (http://bit.ly/1CXTj4V) THE STANDARD -- Occupy Central organizers are planning a carnival-like atmosphere for their civil disobedience campaign, while hinting the kick-off date could be National Day on Oct. 1. (http://bit.ly/1tEhbnD) -- Bedding material producer Sinomax <1418.HK> plans to open more outlets, dubbed Life Stores, in local and mainland shopping malls. Chief executive Eric Cheung Dung said four shops will open in Hong Kong and four across the border. The firm, which listed in July, will also launch more mattresses and massage armchair products. (http://bit.ly/1BwfkGx) -- Underlying profit of Sun Hung Kai Properties <0016.HK> is estimated to have risen up to 23 percent in the fiscal year ending June 30 from the previous 12-month period. Estimates by analysts vary between HK$19.2 billion ($2.48 billion) and HK$22.9 billion. (http://bit.ly/X3Czsj)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- China sewage treatment firm Ell Environmental Holdings Ltd plans to sell 200 million shares, raising up to HK$120 million in an initial public offering in Hong Kong.  MING PAO DAILY NEWS  -- Business receipts for the retail industry in Hong Kong fell 7 percent on year in value terms in the second quarter, while business receipts for tourism, convention and exhibition services fell 7.5 percent, according to the Census and Statistic Department. For Chinese newspapers, see...............[PRESS/CN]